   "source": [
    "# Initial inspection shows that several terms appear very frequently across\n",
    "# the corpus, including \"ai\", \"model(s)\", \"human(s)\", \"deployment\", \"safety\",\n",
    "# and \"risk(s)\". While these may initially seem like candidates for removal\n",
    "# alongside standard stopwords, frequency alone is not a sufficient basis\n",
    "# for exclusion.\n",
    "#\n",
    "# The purpose of this step is not to remove common words indiscriminately,\n",
    "# but to distinguish between two types of high-frequency terms:\n",
    "#\n",
    "# (a) words that reflect shared corpus context and offer little value for\n",
    "#     distinguishing topics (e.g., \"ai\", \"model\", company names), and\n",
    "# (b) words that remain substantively meaningful despite their frequency\n",
    "#     (e.g., \"risk\", \"safety\", \"deployment\", \"evaluation\").\n",
    "#\n",
    "# For example, terms such as \"ai\" (3902), \"model\" (3666), and \"system\" (1125)\n",
    "# appear across nearly all documents and primarily signal the domain of the\n",
    "# corpus rather than meaningful variation between documents. In contrast,\n",
    "# terms like \"risk\" (1189), \"safety\" (1720), and \"evaluation(s)\" (1271)\n",
    "# are also frequent, but they capture substantive differences in how\n",
    "# organizations frame governance, harm, and technical practice.\n",
    "\n",
    "#  Based on this inspection:\n",
    "# → I remove corpus-defining terms (low discriminative value)\n",
    "# → I retain frequent but meaningful terms (central to the research question)\n",
    "\n",
    "# This approach reduces\n",
    "# background noise without suppressing the thematic structure the model is intended to uncover.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "3c40340a",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
